    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "On a declining balance loan, interest is calculated based on the remaining principal balance each month. When you make a payment, a portion goes towards the interest accrued since the last payment, and the rest reduces the principal. As the principal balance decreases with each payment, the amount of interest charged in the following months also gets smaller. This is why your principal balance reduces over time, even if your payment amount stays the same.",
      "source": "target",
