    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get that, but it feels like there are these hidden costs or something eating away at my progress. like, why does it feel so much slower at the beginning compared to later on? is there a specific way the math works to favor the lender in those early years?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The reason it feels slower at the beginning is that in the early repayment stages, a much larger portion of your fixed monthly payment is allocated to covering the accrued interest rather than reducing the principal. Because the principal balance is highest at the start, the interest charge is at its maximum level. This initial allocation emphasizes interest coverage, which naturally slows the reduction of the core loan amount compared to later years when the interest portion is smaller.",
